<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-07-21T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-07-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="866" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d866">
                                <note rend="inline" type="source">840.50 <gloss target="#t_UNRRA1"><hi rend="smallcaps">unrra</hi></gloss>/7–2145:
                                    Telegram</note>
                                <head>No. 866<lb/><hi rend="italic">The Assistant Secretary of
                                        State</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_CWL1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Clayton</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">and the Director of the Office of Financial and Development
                                        Policy</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_CEG1" type="to"><hi rend="italic">Collado</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Department of State</hi><note n="1" xml:id="d866fn1">Sent to the Acting Secretary of State over the signature of
                                            <persName corresp="#p_BJF1">Byrnes</persName>.</note></head>
                                <opener>
                                    <seg rendition="#left"><hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi></seg>
                                    <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Babelsberg</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-07-21">July 21,
                                            1945</date>.</dateline>
                                </opener>
                                <p><gloss target="#t_Victory1"><hi rend="smallcaps">Victory</hi></gloss> 182. For <persName corresp="#p_TWL1">Thorp</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_GDS1">Gilpatric</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_RJJ1">Reinstein</persName> from <persName corresp="#p_CWL1">Clayton</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_CEG1">Collado</persName>.</p>
                                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                                <p>British and we are pressing re German imports for joint financing
                                    and first charge principle. At technical level Soviets seem
                                    prepared to enter joint financing if any small amount is needed
                                    but balk at first charge principle, although they recognize the
                                    necessity of paying for any approved imports. Matter referred to
                                    Foreign Ministers for decision.</p>
                            </div>
                            </body></text></TEI>